      <hedline>
        <hl1>Cautious on Korea</hl1>
      </hedline>
      <abstract>
        <p>Edward W Poitras letter says 'cautious optimism' is best response to Korean summit; says US should support South Korean Pres Kim Dae Jung in any attempts to move out of confrontation mode with North (June 16 article)</p>
      </abstract>
    </body.head>
    <body.content>
      <block class="lead_paragraph">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>The cliche ''cautious optimism'' may be the best response yet to the summit meeting between the leaders of North and South Korea (front page, June 16).</p>
        <p>Optimism seems appropriate, since the basis for constructive negotiation in Korea has traditionally been the laying of a foundation of personal relationships. Caution seems necessary because of the pervasive North Korean philosophy of juche, a glorified, extreme self-determination.</p>
      </block>
      <block class="full_text">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>The cliche ''cautious optimism'' may be the best response yet to the summit meeting between the leaders of North and South Korea (front page, June 16).</p>
        <p>Optimism seems appropriate, since the basis for constructive negotiation in Korea has traditionally been the laying of a foundation of personal relationships. Caution seems necessary because of the pervasive North Korean philosophy of juche, a glorified, extreme self-determination.</p>
        <p>Surely the most difficult sell for President Kim Jong Il in the North will be to justify having outsiders contribute to the national welfare.  And surely it is time for the United States to shed the vestiges of its cold-war mentality and support President Kim Dae Jung of South Korea in his attempts to find creative paths out of the web of vested interests supporting that outdated confrontation.</p>
        <p>EDWARD W. POITRAS  Freeport, Me., June 16, 2000</p>
        <p>The writer taught history in Seoul for 33 years.</p>
      </block>
